At the end of this course, students are expected:
1. to become familiar with the different stages of curriculum design and the core issues in each stage;
2. to acquire the basic principles of curriculum design and the practical skills for developing curriculum;
3. to understand the relationship between curriculum development in Hong Kong and the school curriculum.

courses.course_syllabus:
1. The definitions of curriculum;
2. Relationships between curriculum, instruction and assessment;
3. The commonplaces of curriculum design;
4. Curriculum aims and objectives;
5. Selection and organization of learning experiences;
6. Student assessment and curriculum evaluation;
7. Models of curriculum design.

courses.learning_outcomes:
At the end of this course, students are expected to be able to:

1. Identify the key features of various teaching models and pedagogical orientations;
2. State the merits and demerits of various teaching models and pedagogical orientations;
3. Apply the basic principles of various teaching models and pedagogical orientations to real-life instructional design;
4. Reflect critically on the current practice in schools and explore the possibilities of improving classroom teaching.

At the end of this course, students are expected to be able to:

(1) state the basic concepts of curriculum evaluation;
(2) list the key criteria for evaluating curriculum guides, textbooks and school-based curricula;
(3) analyze why the implemented curriculum must be evaluated;
(4) construct appropriate assessment tasks to collect information on the learned curriculum;
(5) examine critically some current issues related to curriculum evaluation in Hong Kong.

