courses.learning_outcomes:
1. describe the basic literary theories and different genres of children’s literature;
2. examine the characteristics and educational functions of children’s literature, and employ various forms of children’s literary works in their teaching; and
3. apply the theories and methods for appreciating and teaching children’s literature in literacy education.

courses.course_syllabus:
1. the significance, characteristics and educational functions of children’s literature;
2. the features of various forms of children’s literature (e.g., nursery rhymes, children’s poetry, fairy tales, biographies, stories, mythologies, fables, fictions, proses, and picture books); and
3. the appreciation and teaching of children’s literature: to build around the basic theory and knowledge of different genres of children’s literature, and interwoven with the reading and appreciation of works in various genres, it leads participants to explore the teaching activities and strategies in relation to the application of children’s literature in teaching, so as to develop young learners’ literacy.

courses.learning_outcomes:
Upon completion of the course, participants should be able to:
1. understand the theories, characteristics, and practices of play;
2. design and implement play activities to foster young children’s language, cognitive, social, emotional, and physical development;
3. design and set up play environments;
4. develop resources for play activities;
5. assessing children's learning and development in play; and
6. perform the roles of supporter and facilitator in children’s learning in play.

At the end of the course, participants are expected to be able to:
• recognise and articulate the essence and role of STEM education in the 21st century;
• identify various pedagogical and curriculum approaches to STEM education;
• design STEM lessons and materials to meet student needs in primary education;
• develop and implement authentic assessments for STEM activities;
• implement STEM oriented activities in both formal and informal curriculum.

